    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Dynamena huttoni</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_459",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Diverse genus of flatted, rounded isopods that quickly roll into a ball when disturbed. First five abdominal segments fused together, sixth segment fused to telson to form a ‘pleotelson’ the tips of which are characteristically rolled downwards in this genus to form a ‘gutter’.&nbsp;</p><p>This species is identified by its smooth body, which lacks any tubercles or granules, and by its convex, domed pleotelson and the broadly rounded tips to the uropods. Colour can range from cream to pink or red.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_460",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reported in literature to grow up to 18 mm (excluding antennae) but all examples we have seen are smaller than 10 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_461",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Southern Africa, New Zealand and sub-Antarctic Islands.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to southern KwaZulu-Natal.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_462",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Poorly known, but found common amongst seaweeds and under boulders in intertidal and on shallow subtidal reefs.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_463",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Presumed to feed on algae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_464",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Like all isopods the eggs are released into a marsupium between the walking legs of the female, where they are fertilized by the male and develop into fully-formed juveniles before being released.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_465",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>There are 10 regional species in this genus, many of them common among intertidal algae. They are separated by body shape, dorsal ornamentation (smooth or with dorsal tubercles) and by pleotelson shape, ornamentation and type of terminal notch. The smooth body separates this species from all other regional representatives of the genus.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_466",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 92).<br><br>Kensley, B (1978). Guide to the Marine Isopods of Southern Africa. <i>Trustees of the South African Museum</i>, Cape Town. 173 pp. (p. 92).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_467",
